Report timing of CmdStan runs

Source: R/fit.R
fit-method-time.Rd

Report the run time in seconds. For MCMC additional information is provided about the run times of individual chains and the warmup and sampling phases.

Usage

$time()

Value

A list with elements

  • total: (scalar) the total run time.

  • chains: (data frame) for MCMC only, timing info for the individual chains. The data frame has columns "chain_id", "warmup", "sampling", and "total".

See also

CmdStanMCMC, CmdStanMLE, CmdStanVB

Examples

# \dontrun{
fit_mcmc <- cmdstanr_example("logistic", method = "sample")
#> Model executable is up to date!
fit_mcmc$time()
#> $total
#> [1] 0.552681
#> 
#> $chains
#>   chain_id      warmup    sampling     total
#> 1        1 0.004246950 0.003657103 0.1272390
#> 2        2 0.004976034 0.003442049 0.1288078
#> 3        3 0.003338099 0.002820015 0.1225679
#> 4        4 0.003430843 0.002821922 0.1242170
#> 

fit_mle <- cmdstanr_example("logistic", method = "optimize")
#> Model executable is up to date!
fit_mle$time()
#> $total
#> [1] 0.01351094
#> 

fit_vb <- cmdstanr_example("logistic", method = "variational")
#> Model executable is up to date!
fit_vb$time()
#> $total
#> [1] 0.03305221
#> 
# }
